articles.author: Nidal Al-Mughrabi, Kamel Hamdan
articles.description: Israeli forces advanced further on Sunday into the Shejaia neighbourhood of northern Gaza and also pushed deeper into western and central Rafah in the south, killing at least six Palestinians and destroying several homes, residents said.
articles.title: Israeli tanks advance into areas in north and south Gaza, fighting rages

articles.author: Johnny Cotton
articles.description: French voters cast their ballots on Sunday in the first round of a snap parliamentary election that could usher in the country's first far-right government since World War Two, a potential sea change at the heart of the European Union.
articles.title: France to vote in election that could put far right in government

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Myanmar's central bank denied a U.N. report that the country's military government can still access money and weapons for its war against anti-coup forces, saying financial institutions under the bank's supervision followed prescribed procedures.
articles.title: Myanmar central bank denies UN report on weapons transactions

articles.author: Hyunsu Yim
articles.description: North Korean officials wore pins with a portrait of Kim Jong Un in public for the first time in pictures released by state media on Sunday, the latest step in the development of a cult of personality about the leader.
articles.title: North Korean officials sport Kim Jong Un pins for first time

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: South African parties are close to reaching a deal on who gets which cabinet posts, local media reported on Sunday, the last hurdle to setting up a government after the ruling party lost its majority in an election for the first time in three decades.
articles.title: South African parties close to reaching deal on cabinet, local media reports

articles.author: Hyunsu Yim, Ju-Min Park
articles.description: North Korea criticised a joint military exercise by South Korea, Japan and the United States held this month, state media said on Sunday, saying such drills show the relationship among three countries has developed into "the Asian version of NATO".
articles.title: North Korea blames South Korea, U.S. and Japan ties as Asian version of NATO

articles.author: Ted Hesson, Alexandra Ulmer
articles.description:
Minutes before going on stage for the first presidential debate on Thursday, Donald Trump received a phone call from the mother of 12-year-old Jocelyn Nungaray, who was killed in Houston this month, allegedly by two Venezuelan men in the U.S. illegally.
The mother, Alexis Nungaray, was returning a voicemail Trump had left earlier in the day when she was at her daughter's funeral, a friend of the f
articles.title: Trump puts murdered women and girls center stage in anti-immigration drive

articles.author: John Kruzel, Andrew Goudsward
articles.description: Donald Trump's bid for criminal immunity from prosecution for trying to overturn his 2020 election loss is set to be decided on Monday by the U.S. Supreme Court. But however it rules, the court already has helped the former president in his effort to avoid trial before the Nov. 5 election.
articles.title: US Supreme Court's slow pace on immunity makes Trump trial before election unlikely

articles.author: Lucinda Elliott
articles.description: Uruguayans take to the polls on Sunday in primary elections ahead of October's presidential race, in which the left-wing opposition is seen edging ahead according to opinion polls with voters concerned about rising inequality and public safety.
articles.title: Uruguay holds primary elections as opposition left gains ground

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Top Orthodox Christian clergy from across Europe and Bulgaria's senior government officials gathered in Sofia's main cathedral on Sunday for the enthronement of the new patriarch of the country's influential church.
articles.title: Bulgaria's new patriarch enthroned in Sofia cathedral
